org.as2lib.ant
Class Mtasc

java.lang.Object
  org.apache.tools.ant.ProjectComponent
      org.apache.tools.ant.Task
          org.as2lib.ant.Mtasc
Direct Known Subclasses:
Swf
public class Mtasc
extends org.apache.tools.ant.Task

Mtasc compiles ActionScript 2 classes with the Motion-Twin ActionScript Compiler MTASC in Apache Ant as Ant Task.

You must therefor daclare your custom task definition:

<taskdef name="mtasc" classname="org.as2lib.ant.Mtasc"/>

It is now possible to reference the task by the tag/task name "mtasc". For example:

<mtasc src="${src.dir}/Application.as" classpath="${src.dir}" main="true" swf="${src.dir}/app.swf"/>

It is of course also possible to declare not only one source file but a whole source directory. Note that this also includes the files of the sub-directories.

<mtasc srcdir="${src.dir}/org/as2lib" classpath="${src.dir}" split="yes"/>

In case you only want to compile classes matching a given pattern you can use "srcset". 

<mtasc classpath="${src.dir}" split="yes">
  <srcset dir="${src.dir}">
    <include name="**/*Queue.as"/>
    <include name="**/*Map.as"/>
  </srcset>
</mtasc>

If the mtasc executable is not included as environment variable in your operating system you must either include it or set it yourself for every mtasc-tag using the "mtasc" attribute. Take a look at setMtasc(String) for more information.

This task can take the following arguments:

  • src
  • srcdir
  • srcset
  • srcxml
  • pack or package
  • packset
  • classpath
  • verbose
  • strict
  • msvc
  • mx
  • keep
  • group
  • separate (MTASC versions rc2 to 1.08)
  • version
  • flash6 (MTASC versions 1.04 to 1.08)
  • main
  • swf
  • out
  • frame
  • header
  • excl or exclude
  • trace
  • help
  • mtasc
  • split
  • infer
  • wimp
  • argument

You must either provide "src", "srcdir", "srcset", "srcxml", "pack" or "packset".

setMtasc

public void setMtasc(java.lang.String mtasc)
Sets the path to or name of the mtasc executable.

The path can either be an absolute path: E:/Programming/Flash/mtasc/mtasc.exe

or a relative path: lib/mtasc/hamtasc.exe

You may also just use the name of the executable (without the file extension) if the directory it resides in is included in the 'PATH' environment variable: hamtasc

If you do not set a mtasc executable MTASC will be used. This requires that you include the directory in which the mtasc executable resides in the 'PATH' environment variable.

Parameters:
mtasc - the path to or name of the mtasc executable

createArgument

public Mtasc.Argument createArgument()
Creates a new custom argument.

Custom arguments can be used to leverage the functionality offfered by enhanced MTASC compilers like Hacked MTASC (HAMTASC) from Ralf Bokelberg. Custom arguments allow you to specify your own name-value pairs or flags that shall be included in the resulting command.

You can for example specify an assert function when compiling with HAMTASC. This would result in -rb_assert MyClass.myFunction being added to the command. <argument name="-rb_assert" value="MyClass.myFunction"/>

You can also add flags by not specifying a value. <argument name="-rb_check_void_parameter"/>

Returns:
the new argument
